subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.

Philoctetes acuminatus


sp. nov.

is characterised by having conical and apically pointed metanotum (
Fig. 3C
); female face dimorphic, with lenticular shape; female scapal basin entirely polished (
Fig. 3B
), male scapal basin with or without irregular, shallow wrinkles (
Fig. 3E
); mesosoma with long, black and erect setae (
Figs 3C, 3G
); metasoma with shorter, whitish setae (
Figs 3D, 3H
); mesoscutum with shallow punctures, irregularly sparse in female (
Fig. 3A
), mostly clumped along notauli in male (
Fig. 3I
); metasomal apical notch deep, with thickened and darkened apical margin; male tergum II dorsally black (
Fig. 3H
).

Male
(3E–3J). Body length 4.0 mm. Smaller than female. Head unmodified, triangular (
Fig. 3E
); vertex, from ocellar triangle to occiput, widely impunctate, punctures sparse and shallow; mesoscutum less punctate (
Fig. 3I
), widely polished in 
one paratype
, with shallow punctures along notauli; mesoscutellum ending in short, raised, median prominence (
Fig. 3G
); greenish head and mesosoma (
Fig. 3G
), tergum I–II black dorsally, without metallic reflections (
Fig. 3H
). Genitalia as seen in 
Fig. 3F–3J
.
